children: The Office Story: That's what the data said
Analyzing character stats,relationships and their influence on popularity of
‘The Office’ TV show through interactive visualizations using Plotly,d3graph
and chord packages.
Source: Giphy, The Office GIF By NBC
Presented by Swarnita Venkatraman

(b) Goal - To determine what kind of questions can be answered from the show's script and ratings data analysis that can lead the makers to better data-driven decisions while investing in a potential revival/reboot.
(a) Performed data pre-processing, feature engineering and data analysis on the show's dialogues dataset from theofficequotes.net and IMDB ratings dataset from Kaggle.

Did all characters get their due — did the characters appear in as many scenes/episodes when compared to the number of lines they spoke?
Question 1:

The smaller gap between the number of lines(line chart)and scenes(bar chart) for supporting characters suggests that they had much lesser lines compared to the scenes they appeared in as opposed to the top 5 characters indicating the significance placed on their screen presence.

Question 4:
In depth analysis of the four major character relationships
over 9 seasons — How do they influence the ratings?

The four character relationships seem to be in focus between season 2–5(though a dip seen in season 4 is possibly because it had only 14 episodes) after which their share of lines and scenes decrease with the focus shifting to newly introduced character story arcs when Michael leaves the show in season 7.
Since the R² values are also very less for all 4 pairs, the total lines spoken by them do not significantly affect the ratings.
Who spoke the most in every episode throughout the show —
How does it influence the ratings?
Question 5:

Michael’s good ratings range and high median rating confirms his role as the central character to retain continuity in episodes while after his departure season 8 and 9’s erratic plotlines and ratings dip can be linked to Andy and Dwight’s high lines and low ratings range.
Question 6:
Exploration of Female representation in the show-
Did the female characters get their due with respect to the number of lines spoken?

Female characters do not have a major share of lines in episodes meant to be centered around women like “Sexual Harassment” (24%), “Boys and Girls” ( 40%) and “Women’s appreciation” (31%); considering half the episodes of the show lie in the 25–50% lines category

Amongst the season-wise highest percentage of lines episodes, female characters had maximum lines in just two episodes —  Erin in “Secretary’s day” and Pam in “Lice”(this was also the only episode where the 50% of lines mark is crossed).
Source : Giphy,Season 1 Nbc GIF By The Office
An Office revival/reboot may or may not be on cards but successful analysis of a show’s ratings,script and character stats(arcs and relationships) enables better data-driven
decision making for the makers to identify and invest confidently in what the viewers
prefer and what more would they like to see in a revival/reboot.
